# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: database-sharding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] In computer science, **consistent hashing** is a special kind of hashing technique such that when a hash table is resized, only $n/m$ keys need to be remapped on average where n is the number of keys and m is the number of slots.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing evenly distributes cache keys across shards, even if some of the shards crash or become unavailable.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] In contrast, in most traditional hash tables, a change in the number of array slots causes nearly all keys to be remapped because the mapping between the keys and the slots is defined by a modular operation.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is used by Content Delivery Networks because it is useful for distributing requests for content from a rotating population of web servers.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Tim Berners-Lee credits consistent hashing algorithms, and Daniel Lewin as their inventor, with solving the slashdotting problem which plagued the World Wide Web in the 1990s.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The term "consistent hashing" was introduced by David Karger *et al.* at MIT for use in distributed caching, particularly for the web.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] This academic paper from 1997 in Symposium on Theory of Computing introduced the term "consistent hashing" as a way of distributing requests among a changing population of web servers.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Each slot is then represented by a server in a distributed system or cluster.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The addition of a server and the removal of a server (during scalability or outage) requires only $num\_keys/num\_slots$ items to be re-shuffled when the number of slots (i.e. servers) change.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The authors mention linear hashing and its ability to handle sequential server addition and removal, while consistent hashing allows servers to be added and removed in an arbitrary order.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The paper was later re-purposed to address technical challenge of keeping track of a file in peer-to-peer networks such as a distributed hash table.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Teradata used this technique in their distributed database, released in 1986, although they did not use this term.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Teradata still uses the concept of a hash table to fulfill exactly this purpose.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Akamai Technologies was founded in 1998 by the scientists Daniel Lewin and F.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Thomson Leighton (co-authors of the article coining "consistent hashing").
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] In Akamai's content delivery network, consistent hashing is used to balance the load within a cluster of servers, while a stable marriage algorithm is used to balance load across clusters.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing has also been used to reduce the impact of partial system failures in large web applications to provide robust caching without incurring the system-wide fallout of a failure.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is also the cornerstone of distributed hash tables (DHTs), which employ hash values to partition a keyspace across a distributed set of nodes, then construct an overlay network of connected nodes that provide efficient node retrieval by key.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique .
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] It achieves the goals of consistent hashing using the very different highest random weight (HRW) algorithm.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] However, when a server is added or removed during outage or scaling (when n changes), all the BLOBs in every server should be reassigned and moved due to rehashing, but this operation is expensive.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing was designed to avoid the problem of having to reassign every BLOB when a server is added or removed throughout the cluster.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The central idea is to use a hash function that maps both the BLOB and servers to a unit circle, usually $2\pi$ radians.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] For example, $\zeta =\Phi \ \%\ 360$ (where $\Phi$ is hash of a BLOB or server's identifier, like IP address or UUID).
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Each BLOB is then assigned to the next server that appears on the circle in clockwise order.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] This provides an even distribution of BLOBs to servers.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] But, more importantly, if a server fails and is removed from the circle, only the BLOBs that were mapped to the failed server need to be reassigned to the next server in clockwise order.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Likewise, if a new server is added, it is added to the unit circle, and only the BLOBs mapped to that server need to be reassigned.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Importantly, when a server is added or removed, the vast majority of the BLOBs maintain their prior server assignments, and the addition of $n^{th}$ server only causes $1/n$ fraction of the BLOBs to relocate.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Although the process of moving BLOBs across cache servers in the cluster depends on the context, commonly, the newly added cache server identifies its "predecessor" and moves all the BLOBs, whose mapping belongs to this server (i.e. whose hash value is less than that of the new server), from it.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] However, in the case of web page caches, in most implementations there is no involvement of moving or copying, assuming the cached BLOB is small enough.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] When a request hits a newly added cache server, a cache miss happens and a request to the actual web server is made and the BLOB is cached locally for future requests.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The redundant BLOBs on the previously used cache servers would be removed as per the cache eviction policies.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Let $h_{b}(x)$ and $h_{s}(x)$ be the hash functions used for the BLOB and server's unique identifier respectively.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] In practice, a binary search tree (BST) is used to dynamically maintain the ${\text{server ID}}$ within a cluster or hashring, and to find the successor or minimum within the BST, tree traversal is used.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] To avoid skewness of multiple nodes within the radian, which happen due to lack of uniform distribution of the servers within the cluster, multiple labels are used.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Those duplicate labels are called "virtual nodes" i.e. multiple labels which point to a single "real" label or server within the cluster.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The amount of virtual nodes or duplicate labels used for a particular server within a cluster is called the "weight" of that particular server.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] A number of extensions to the basic technique are needed for effectively using consistent hashing for load balancing in practice.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] In the basic scheme above, if a server fails, all its BLOBs are reassigned to the next server in clockwise order, potentially doubling the load of that server.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] To ensure a more even redistribution of BLOBs on server failure, each server can be hashed to multiple locations on the unit circle.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] When a server fails, the BLOBs assigned to each of its replicas on the unit circle will get reassigned to a different server in clockwise order, thus redistributing the BLOBs more evenly.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Another extension concerns a situation where a single BLOB gets "hot" and is accessed a large number of times and will have to be hosted in multiple servers.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] In this situation, the BLOB may be assigned to multiple contiguous servers by traversing the unit circle in clockwise order.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] A more complex practical consideration arises when two BLOBs are hashed near each other in the unit circle and both get "hot" at the same time.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] In this case, both BLOBs will use the same set of contiguous servers in the unit circle.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] This situation can be ameliorated by each BLOB choosing a different hash function for mapping servers to the unit circle.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique, and permits fully distributed agreement on a set of k options out of a possible set of n options.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] It can in fact be shown that consistent hashing is a special case of rendezvous hashing.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] Because of its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being used in place of Consistent Hashing in many applications.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] If key values will always increase monotonically, an alternative approach using a hash table with monotonic keys may be more suitable than consistent hashing.
[src:database-sharding/consistent-hashing] The $O(K/N)$ is an average cost for redistribution of keys and the $O(\log N)$ complexity for consistent hashing comes from the fact that a binary search among nodes angles is required to find the next node on the ring.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:database-sharding/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] A **partition** is a division of a logical database or its constituent elements into distinct independent parts.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Database partitioning refers to intentionally breaking a large database into smaller ones for scalability purposes, distinct from network partitions which are a type of network fault between nodes.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] In a partitioned database, each piece of data belongs to exactly one partition, effectively making each partition a small database of its own.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Database partitioning is normally done for manageability, performance or availability reasons, or for load balancing.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] It is popular in distributed database management systems, where each partition may be spread over multiple nodes, with users at the node performing local transactions on the partition.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] This increases performance for sites that have regular transactions involving certain views of data, whilst maintaining availability and security.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Partitioning enables distribution of datasets across multiple disks and query loads across multiple processors.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] For queries that operate on a single partition, each node executes queries independently on its local partition, enabling linear scaling of query throughput with additional nodes.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] More complex queries can be parallelized across multiple nodes, though this presents additional challenges.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Database partitioning emerged in the 1980s with systems like Teradata and NonStop SQL.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] The approach was later adopted by NoSQL databases and Hadoop-based data warehouses.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] While implementations vary between transactional and analytical workloads, the core principles of partitioning remain consistent across both use cases.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Partitioning is commonly implemented alongside replication, storing partition copies across multiple nodes.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Each record belongs to one partition but may exist on multiple nodes for fault tolerance.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] In leader-follower replication systems, nodes can simultaneously serve as leaders for some partitions and followers for others.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Partitioning aims to distribute data and query load evenly across nodes.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] With ideal distribution, system capacity scales linearly with added nodes—ten nodes should process ten times the data and throughput of a single node.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Uneven distribution, termed *skew*, reduces partitioning efficiency.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Partitions with excessive load are called *hot spots*.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Current high-end relational database management systems provide for different criteria to split the database.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] They take a *partitioning key* and assign a partition based on certain criteria.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] In any partitioning scheme, data is typically arranged so that each piece of data (record, row, or document) belongs to exactly one partition.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] While some databases support operations that span multiple partitions, this single-partition association is fundamental to the partitioning concept.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] The partitioning can be done by either building separate smaller databases (each with its own tables, indices, and transaction logs), or by splitting selected elements, for example just one table.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Horizontal partitioning involves putting different rows into different tables.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] For example, customers with ZIP codes less than 50000 are stored in CustomersEast, while customers with ZIP codes greater than or equal to 50000 are stored in CustomersWest.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] The two partition tables are then CustomersEast and CustomersWest, while a view with a union might be created over both of them to provide a complete view of all customers.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Vertical partitioning involves creating tables with fewer columns and using additional tables to store the remaining columns.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Generally, this practice is known as normalization.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] However, vertical partitioning extends further, and partitions columns even when already normalized.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] This type of partitioning is also called "row splitting", since rows get split by their columns, and might be performed explicitly or implicitly.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Distinct physical machines might be used to realize vertical partitioning: storing infrequently used or very wide columns, taking up a significant amount of memory, on a different machine, for example, is a method of vertical partitioning.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] A common form of vertical partitioning is to split static data from dynamic data, since the former is faster to access than the latter, particularly for a table where the dynamic data is not used as often as the static.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] Creating a view across the two newly created tables restores the original table with a performance penalty, but accessing the static data alone will show higher performance.
[src:database-sharding/partition-database] A columnar database can be regarded as a database that has been vertically partitioned until each column is stored in its own table.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] A **quorum** is the minimum number of votes that a distributed transaction has to obtain in order to be allowed to perform an operation in a distributed system.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] A **quorum**-based technique is implemented to enforce consistent operation in a distributed system.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Quorum-based voting can be used as a replica control method, as well as a commit method to ensure transaction atomicity in the presence of network partitioning.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] In a distributed database system, a transaction could execute its operations at multiple sites.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Since atomicity requires every distributed transaction to be atomic, the transaction must have the same fate (commit or abort) at every site.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] In case of network partitioning, sites are partitioned and the partitions may not be able to communicate with each other.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] This is where a quorum-based technique comes in.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The fundamental idea is that a transaction is executed if the majority of sites vote to execute it.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Every site in the system is assigned a vote Vi.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Let us assume that the total number of votes in the system is V and the abort and commit quorums are Va and Vc, respectively.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Before a transaction commits, it must obtain a commit quorum Vc.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The total of at least one site that is prepared to commit and zero or more sites waiting $\geq$ Vc.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Before a transaction aborts, it must obtain an abort quorum Va The total of zero or more sites that are prepared to abort or any sites waiting $\geq$ Va.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The first rule ensures that a transaction cannot be committed and aborted at the same time.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The next two rules indicate the votes that a transaction has to obtain before it can terminate one way or the other.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] In replicated databases, a data object has copies present at several sites.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] To ensure serializability, no two transactions should be allowed to read or write a data item concurrently.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] In case of replicated databases, a quorum-based replica control protocol can be used to ensure that no two copies of a data item are read or written by two transactions concurrently.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The quorum-based voting for replica control is due to [Gifford, 1979].
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Each copy of a replicated data item is assigned a vote.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Each operation then has to obtain a *read quorum* (Vr) or a *write quorum* (Vw) to read or write a data item, respectively.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The first rule ensures that a data item is not read and written by two transactions concurrently.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] Additionally, it ensures that a read quorum contains at least one site with the newest version of the data item.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The second rule ensures that two write operations from two transactions cannot occur concurrently on the same data item.
[src:database-sharding/quorum-distributed-computing] The two rules ensure that one-copy serializability is maintained.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] A **database shard**, or simply a **shard**, is a horizontal partition of data within a database or search engine.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Each shard may be held on a separate database server instance in order to spread across multiple servers.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Some data in a database may remain present in all shards, while other data is stored in only one shard.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] In such cases, each shard acts as the single source for its subset of data.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] There are numerous advantages to the horizontal partitioning of data.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Since tables are divided and distributed into multiple servers, the total number of rows in each table in each database is reduced.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This reduces index size, which generally improves search performance.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] A database shard can be placed on separate hardware, and multiple shards can be placed on multiple machines.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This enables the distribution of a database across a large number of machines, which can significantly improve performance.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] In addition, if the database shard is based on some real-world segmentation of the data (e.g., European customers v.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] American customers) it may be possible to infer the appropriate shard membership easily and automatically, and to query only the relevant shard.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Although it has long been implemented through manual coding (especially where rows have an obvious grouping, as in the customer region example above), this approach is often inflexible.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] There is a desire to support sharding automatically, both in terms of adding code support for it, and for identifying candidates to be sharded separately.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Consistent hashing is a technique used in sharding to distribute large loads across multiple smaller services and servers.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Where distributed computing is used to separate load between multiple servers (either for performance or reliability reasons), a sharding approach may also be useful.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] In the 2010s, sharding of execution capacity, as well as the more traditional sharding of data, emerged as a potential approach to address performance and scalability challenges in blockchains.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Recent academic work has proposed protocols such as Cerberus to address cross-shard atomicity by braiding consensus across multiple shards, allowing transactions to affect multiple partitions simultaneously without requiring a global lock.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Horizontal partitioning splits one or more tables by row, usually within a *single* instance of a schema and a database server.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] It partitions the relevant table or tables in the same way, but does so across potentially *multiple* instances of the schema.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] An advantage is that the search load for the large partitioned table can be distributed across multiple servers (logical or physical), rather than only across multiple indexes on a same logical server.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Splitting shards across multiple isolated instances requires more than simple horizontal partitioning.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] The expected gains in efficiency would be reduced if querying the database required *multiple* instances to be accessed just to retrieve a simple dimension table.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Beyond partitioning, sharding therefore involves distributing large, partitionable tables across servers, while smaller tables are replicated in full on each server.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This is also why sharding is related to a shared-nothing architecture—once sharded, each shard can reside in a separate logical schema instance, physical database server, data center, or geographic region.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is intended to minimize the need for cross-shard access by partitioning data across independent shards.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This makes replication across multiple servers easier (simple horizontal partitioning does not).
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] It is also useful for worldwide distribution of applications, where communications links between data centers might otherwise become a bottleneck.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] There is also a requirement for some notification and replication mechanism between schema instances, so that unpartitioned tables remain as closely synchronized as the application requires.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This is a complex architectural choice in sharded systems: approaches range from making these tables effectively read-only (with updates that are rare and batched), to dynamically replicated tables (at the cost of reducing some of the distribution benefits of sharding), and many options in between.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Sharding a database table before it has been optimized locally can introduce unnecessary complexity.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is generally recommended when other optimization strategies have proven insufficient.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] The added complexity of database sharding can result in several potential challenges.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Richard Garriott, creator of *Ultima Online*, recalled that the term originated during the production of the game, specifically in creating a self-regulating, virtual ecology system.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Players were able to interact and harvest in-game resources via the internet, which disrupted the balance of the system.
[src:database-sharding/shard-database-architecture] The feature was later removed after several months of testing.
